Trump has spent the last few weeks ratcheting up tensions in Chicagoland, ultimately making the situation worse for everyone. I want to be clear: I unequivocally condemn violence against immigrants and law enforcement alike. I support protests against federal incursion, but it must always remain peaceful. As for Trump, for the second time this week, I am calling on him to help lower the temperature rather than making the situation worse.

Political violence is abhorrent and is undeniably spreading in our country. It is vital that leaders across the political spectrum play a role in lowering the temperature of our political discourse. If Americans fear that expressing their political views will lead to violence, it becomes impossible to engage in open debate, and the entire democratic system will fail.

Yesterday, there were two instances of horrifying gun violence on school campuses. My thoughts are with the students and families of Evergreen High School in Colorado, the students of Utah Valley in the wake of Charlie Kirk's shooting, and his young family that has joined the ranks of those who have lost a member of their family to a bullet.
 
Gun violence does not care about race, citizenship status, income level, or political affiliation. There are things Congress could and should do to end this scourge right now, and any failure to do so is a dereliction of our duty.
